                individuate theoretical content: any such commitment
                entails a corresponding standard of equivalence.}
}

@article{barrett2022count,
  author   = {Thomas William Barrett},
  title    = {How to Count Structure},
  journal  = {No{\^u}s},
  volume   = {56},
  number   = {2},
  pages    = {295--322},
  year     = {2022},
  doi      = {10.1111/nous.12392},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Develops a framework for comparing the amounts of structure
              that theories posit, using Beth's and Svenonius' definability
              theorems. Connects equivalence criteria to questions of
              ontological parsimony.}
}

@article{halvorson2012scientific,
  author   = {Hans Halvorson},
  title    = {What Scientific Theories Could Not Be},
  journal  = {Philosophy of Science},
  volume   = {79},
  number   = {2},
  pages    = {183--206},
  year     = {2012},
  doi      = {10.1086/664745},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Argues that the semantic (model-theoretic) view of theories
              cannot individuate scientific theories correctly: it conflates
              distinct theories and is insensitive to differences that matter
              for equivalence. The paper that initiated the main contemporary
              exchange on formal criteria.}
}

@article{glymour2013theoretical,
  author   = {Clark Glymour},
  title    = {Theoretical Equivalence and the Semantic View of Theories},
  journal  = {Philosophy of Science},
  volume   = {80},
  number   = {2},
  pages    = {286--297},
  year     = {2013},
  doi      = {10.1086/670261},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Response to Halvorson 2012. Defends a weaker criterion based on
              isomorphism of model categories and argues it captures the cases
              that philosophically matter.}
}

@article{halvorson2013semantic,
  author   = {Hans Halvorson},
  title    = {The Semantic View, If Plausible, Is Syntactic},
  journal  = {Philosophy of Science},
  volume   = {80},
  number   = {3},
  pages    = {475--478},
  year     = {2013},
  doi      = {10.1086/671077},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Brief reply to Glymour 2013. Argues that any workable version
              of the semantic view implicitly relies on syntactic structure,
              collapsing the distinction between syntactic and semantic
              approaches.}
}

@article{barrett2017quine,
  author   = {Thomas William Barrett and Hans Halvorson},
  title    = {Quine's Conjecture on Many-Sorted Logic},
  journal  = {Synthese},
  volume   = {194},
  number   = {9},
  pages    = {3563--3582},
  year     = {2017},
  doi      = {10.1007/s11229-016-1107-z},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Proves Quine's conjecture that any many-sorted first-order theory
              is definitionally equivalent to a one-sorted theory. Shows the
              number of sorts is not a genuine feature of theoretical content
              under definitional equivalence.}
}

@article{barrett2017geometry,
  author   = {Thomas William Barrett and Hans Halvorson},
  title    = {From Geometry to Conceptual Relativity},
  journal  = {Erkenntnis},
  volume   = {82},
  number   = {5},
  pages    = {1043--1063},
  year     = {2017},
  doi      = {10.1007/s10670-016-9858-y},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Uses definitional equivalence to sharpen the Poincar\'e
              conventionalism debate: Euclidean and non-Euclidean geometries
              supplemented with appropriate universal forces are definitionally
              equivalent, giving a precise sense in which the choice of geometry
              is conventional.}
}

@article{nguyen2017scientific,
  author   = {James Nguyen},
  title    = {Scientific Representation and Theoretical Equivalence},
  journal  = {Philosophy of Science},
  volume   = {84},
  number   = {5},
  pages    = {982--995},
  year     = {2017},
  doi      = {10.1086/693988},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Connects formal criteria for theoretical equivalence to debates
              about scientific representation. Argues that representational
              considerations can force inequivalence judgments even when
              formal criteria are satisfied.}
}

@article{hudetz2017semantic,
  author   = {Laurenz Hudetz},
  title    = {The Semantic View of Theories and Higher-Order Languages},
  journal  = {Synthese},
  volume   = {196},
  number   = {3},
  pages    = {1131--1149},
  year     = {2019},
  doi      = {10.1007/s11229-017-1502-0},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Shows that formulating the semantic view in higher-order logic
              dissolves apparent differences between syntactic and semantic
              approaches. Bears on whether categorical equivalence captures
              the same notion as definitional equivalence.}
}

@article{dewar2018translating,
  author   = {Neil Dewar},
  title    = {On Translating between Logics},
  journal  = {Analysis},
  volume   = {78},
  number   = {4},
  pages    = {622--630},
  year     = {2018},
  doi      = {10.1093/analys/any001},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Proposes a criterion for when two logics are theoretically
              equivalent, based on the existence of faithful translations
              between them. Shows that syntactic translatability and semantic
              equivalence come apart in general, and argues that the right
              criterion must be sensitive to the inferential role of the
              logical constants.}
}

@article{dewar2019ramsey,
  author   = {Neil Dewar},
  title    = {Ramsey Equivalence},
  journal  = {Erkenntnis},
  volume   = {84},
  number   = {1},
  pages    = {77--99},
  year     = {2019},
  doi      = {10.1007/s10670-017-9948-5},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Proposes a criterion for theoretical equivalence based on
              Ramsey sentences: two theories are Ramsey-equivalent when
              their Ramsey sentences are logically equivalent. Situates
              this criterion relative to definitional equivalence and
              explores its connections to structural realism.}
}

@article{dewar2019supervenience,
  author   = {Neil Dewar},
  title    = {Supervenience, Reduction, and Translation},
  journal  = {Philosophy of Science},
  volume   = {86},
  number   = {5},
  pages    = {942--954},
  year     = {2019},
  doi      = {10.1086/705445},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Clarifies the formal relationships between supervenience,
              reduction, and translation between theories. Shows that
              several notions of reduction and supervenience can be
              explicated in terms of definability, unifying them within
              a common logical framework.}
}

@article{dewar2023interpretation,
  author   = {Neil Dewar},
  title    = {Interpretation and Equivalence; or, Equivalence and Interpretation},
  journal  = {Synthese},
  volume   = {201},
  number   = {4},
  year     = {2023},
  doi      = {10.1007/s11229-023-04102-9},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Examines the relationship between interpretation and
              equivalence between theories, arguing the two are more
              tightly connected than is often supposed. Analyzes several
              formal accounts and considers their philosophical implications.}
}

@article{dewar2023internal,
  author   = {Neil Dewar},
  title    = {On Internal Structure, Categorical Structure, and Representation},
  journal  = {Philosophy of Science},
  volume   = {90},
  number   = {1},
  pages    = {188--195},
  year     = {2023},
  doi      = {10.1017/psa.2022.10},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Distinguishes internal structural equivalence from categorical
              equivalence and argues they come apart in important cases.
              Bears on whether categorical equivalence can serve as a
              sufficient criterion for theoretical equivalence.}
}

@article{dewar2023convention,
  author   = {Neil Dewar},
  title    = {Equivalence and Convention},
  journal  = {Philosophy of Science},
  volume   = {91},
  number   = {5},
  pages    = {1242--1250},
  year     = {2023},
  doi      = {10.1017/psa.2023.148},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Argues that conventional choices---such as which predicates
              to take as primitive---affect whether two theories count as
              equivalent. Connects theoretical equivalence to the broader
              role of convention in scientific language.}
}

@article{teitel2021theoretical,
  author   = {Trevor Teitel},
  title    = {What Theoretical Equivalence Could Not Be},
  journal  = {Philosophical Studies},
  volume   = {178},
  number   = {12},
  pages    = {4119--4149},
  year     = {2021},
  doi      = {10.1007/s11098-021-01639-8},
  keywords = {criteria},
  annote   = {Argues that no purely formal criterion can fully capture
              theoretical equivalence, because equivalence judgments require
              substantive input about which features of a theory carry
              representational significance.}
}

